@startuml diagram-cluster-access
title Connecting to an EMR Cluster — Two Access Patterns

skinparam defaultFontSize 13
skinparam maxMessageSize 140
skinparam participant {
  BackgroundColor #f8f9fa
  BorderColor #6c757d
}
skinparam note {
  BackgroundColor #fff9c4
  BorderColor #f0c040
}
skinparam sequence {
  ArrowColor #333
  LifeLineBorderColor #aaa
}

actor "You\n(laptop)" as You
participant "VS Code\n(local)" as VSCode
participant "Gateway EC2\n(public subnet)" as Gateway
participant "EMR Primary\n(public or private subnet)" as Primary
participant "Spark UI\n(port 4040)" as SparkUI
participant "History Server\n(port 18080)" as HistoryServer

== Pattern A: VS Code Remote SSH (interactive development) ==

note over You, Primary
  **Goal**: run Python cells on the EMR primary node from VS Code on your laptop.
  The Gateway EC2 acts as an SSH jump host. EMR nodes are often in a private subnet
  or behind restrictive security groups, so you "hop" through the Gateway.
end note

You -> VSCode : Open VS Code
VSCode -> Gateway : Remote SSH\n//~/.ssh/config: Host gateway//
Gateway --> VSCode : connected (shell on Gateway)

note over VSCode, Gateway
  **For DuckDB**: you can work right here.
  Open .py files, select "SQL Demo (uv)" kernel,
  run cells. DuckDB reads S3 directly.
end note

VSCode -> Primary : SSH ProxyJump\n//~/.ssh/config: Host emr-primary\n  ProxyJump gateway//
Primary --> VSCode : connected (shell on EMR primary)

note over VSCode, Primary
  **For SparkSQL**: VS Code is now on the EMR primary.
  PySpark is pre-installed. Run cells with the system
  Python or register a kernel with ipykernel.
end note

== Pattern B: SSH tunnels for web UIs (monitoring) ==

note over You, HistoryServer
  **Goal**: access Spark UI, History Server, and YARN ResourceManager
  in your local browser, forwarded through the Gateway.
end note

You -> Gateway : ssh -NL 4040:emr-primary:4040\n       -L 18080:emr-primary:18080\n       -L 8088:emr-primary:8088\n       gateway
Gateway -> Primary : TCP forward

You -> SparkUI : http://localhost:4040\n//live stages, tasks, SQL plans//
You -> HistoryServer : http://localhost:18080\n//completed job DAGs, stage durations//

note over You, SparkUI
  VS Code Remote SSH auto-forwards ports it detects.
  If you open a notebook that prints "SparkUI at :4040",
  VS Code offers to forward it automatically.
end note

== SSH config (one-time setup) ==

note over You, Primary #e8f4e8
  **~/.ssh/config**
  Host gateway
      HostName <gateway-public-ip>
      User ubuntu
      IdentityFile ~/.ssh/your-key.pem

  Host emr-primary
      HostName <emr-primary-private-ip>
      User hadoop
      IdentityFile ~/.ssh/vockey.pem
      ProxyJump gateway

  After this:
    ssh gateway           → DuckDB host
    ssh emr-primary       → EMR primary (via gateway hop)
    VS Code Remote SSH    → either host
end note

@enduml
